label: FGWPB-121
info_overview: FIBARO Wall Plug is a universal, Z-Wave Plus compatible, remotely controlled outlet adapter.
info_inclusion:
To add the device to the Z-Wave network:

  • Plug the device into a socket nearby the main Z-Wave controller.
  • The LED ring will glow red signalling not being added (reset or remove the device otherwise).
  • Set the main controller in (security/non-security) add mode (see the controller’s manual).
  • Quickly, triple click the B-button located on the casing.
  • Wait for the adding process to end.
  • Successful adding will be confirmed by the Z-Wave controller’s message.
info_exclusion:
To remove the device from the Z-Wave network:

  • Plug the device into a socket nearby the main Z-Wave controller.
  • The LED ring will glow green signalling being added (removing is not necessary otherwise).
  • Set the main controller into remove mode (see the controller’s manual).
  • Quickly, triple click the B-button located on the casing.
  • Wait for the removing process to end.
  • Successful removing will be confirmed by the Z-Wave controller’s message.

category_description: Small devices to be plugged into a power socket in a wall which stick there

parameters.label: Power Failure
parameters.description: Remember device status before the power failure.
parameters.overview: This parameter determines how the Wall Plug will react in the event of power supply failure (e.g. power outage or taking out from the electrical outlet). After the power supply is back on, the Wall Plug can be restored to previous state or remain switched off.

options.label: Switched OFF.
options.overview: Device remains switched off when power is restored.

options.label: Restore State.
options.overview: Device restores the state prior to the power failure (default).

parameters.label: Overload
parameters.description: Overload safety switch.
parameters.overview:
0 - function inactive (default).

10-18000 - (1.0-1800.0W, step 0.1W) - power threshold.

This function allows to turn off the controlled device in case of exceeding the defined power. Controlled device can be turned back on via button or sending a control frame. By default this function is inactive.

options.label: Overload Disabled.
options.overview: Disables turning off the controlled device when exceeding the defined power.

parameters.label: PowerReporting
parameters.description: Power reporting.
parameters.overview:
0 - power reports inactive.

1-100 - power change in percent; default 15%.

This parameter determines the minimum percentage change in active power consumption (in relation to the previously reported) that will result in sending new power report.

parameters.label: EnergyReportingThreshold
parameters.description: Energy reporting threshold.
parameters.overview:
0 - energy reports inactive.

1-500 - (0.01-5kWh, step 0.01kWh) - threshold; default 10 (0.1kWh).

parameters.label: ReportingInterval
parameters.description: Periodic power reporting.
parameters.overview:
0 - periodic reports inactive.

30-32400 - In seconds; default 3600 (1h).

This parameter defines time period between independent reports sent when changes in power load have not been recorded or if changes are insignificant. By default reports are sent every hour.

parameters.label: ReportingEnergyInterval
parameters.description: Periodic energy reporting.
parameters.overview:
0 - periodic reports inactive.

30-32400 - In seconds; default 3600 (1h).

This parameter defines time period between independent reports sent when changes in power load have not been recorded or if changes are insignificant. By default reports are sent every hour.

parameters.label: Consumption
parameters.description: Measuring energy consumed by the Wall Plug itself.
parameters.overview: This parameter determines whether power metering should include the amount of power consumed by the Wall Plug itself. Results are being added to the value of power consumed by controlled device.

options.label: Disables energy consumption.
options.overview: Exclude (default) the amount of power consumed by the Wall Plug itself.

options.label: Enables energy consumption.
options.overview: Include the amount of power consumed by the Wall Plug itself.

parameters.label: Up Value
parameters.description: Upper power threshold.
parameters.overview:
[UP value - "On/Off (Power)" association group (3) .]

100-18000 - (10.0-1800.0W, step 0.1W); default 500 (50W).

Upper power threshold, used in parameter 23. UP value cannot be lower than a value specified in parameter 22.

parameters.label: Down value
parameters.description: Lower power threshold.
parameters.overview:
[DOWN value - "On/Off (Power)" association group (3).]

parameters.label: Active Alarms
parameters.description: Network alarms to which the Wall Plug will respond.
parameters.overview: Define Z-Wave network alarms to which the Wall Plug will respond.

parameters.label: Response to alarm frames.
parameters.description: Wall plug response to alarms.
parameters.overview:
5-50 (0.5-5.0s, step 0.1s) - cyclically change device state with set period.

This parameter defines how the Wall Plug will respond to alarms (device’s status change). In case of values 1 or 2 the Wall Plug is operating normally and LED frame signals an alarm through time defined in parameter 32 or until the alarm is canceled. In case of values 5 to 50 the Wall Plug does not report status change, power changes, ignores BASIC SET command frames. After time defined in parameter 32 or after the alarm cancellation, connected device is set to the previous state.

parameters.label: Alarm state duration.
parameters.description: Specifies the duration of the alarm state.
parameters.overview:
1-32400 (in seconds).

600 (default).

This parameter specifies the duration of alarm state. If a device sending an alarm frame through the Z-Wave network sets alarm duration as well, this settings are ignored.

NOTE: The alarm may be canceled by pressing and holding the button.

parameters.label: Power load for violet color.
parameters.description: Maximum active power to flash the LED frame Violet.
parameters.overview:
1000-18000 (100.0-1800.0W, step 0.1W).

18000 (1800W; Default).

This parameter determines maximum active power value, which when exceeded, causes the LED frame to flash violet. Function is active only when parameter 41 is set to 1 or 2.

parameters.label: LED frame color ON.
parameters.description: LED frame color when controlled device is on.
parameters.overview:
When set to 1 or 2, LED frame color will change depending on active power and parameter 40.

Other colors are set permanently and do not depend on power consumption

options.label: Active Power (Smooth).
options.overview: 1 - Color changes smoothly depending on active power.

options.label: Active Power (Steps).
options.overview: 2 - Color changes in steps depending on active power.

parameters.label: LED frame color OFF.
parameters.description: LED frame color when controlled device is off.
parameters.overview: This parameter defines the illumination color after turning off.

options.label: Last Measured Load.
options.overview: 1 - LED frame is illuminated with a color corresponding to the last measured power, before the controlled device was turned off.

parameters.label: LED frame color Z-Wave.
parameters.description: Z-Wave alarm illumination.
parameters.overview: This parameter defines the illumination color in case of Z-Wave alarm.

options.label: No change in color.
options.overview: 1 - No change in color. LED frame color is determined by settings of parameters 41 or 42.

associations.label: Lifeline
associations.overview: 1st Association Group – “Lifeline” (for root, endpoint 1 and 2) reports the device status and allows for assigning single device only (main controller by default).

associations.label: On/Off (Button)

associations.overview: 2nd Association Group – “On/Off (Button)” (for root and endpoint 1) devices in this group will be switched on or off when relay status is changed using the button (uses Basic command class).

associations.label: On/Off (Plug power)
associations.description: Switched On/Off based on the current load of plugged device.
associations.overview: 3rd Association Group – “On/Off (Plug power)” (for root and endpoint 1) devices in this group will be switched on or off depending on the current load of plugged device (uses Basic command class).
